We constructed a stimulated emission depletion microscope (STED) with simultaneous molecular scale resolution (i.e., ten times better than conventional optical microscopes), wavelength tunablilty, and ~500-picosecond time resolution.  The STED system is capable of imaging micron sized features with 40-nm resolution in the focal plane.  The instrument significantly expands the STED microscopy technique to new fluorophores and applications.  The added capacity of time resolution permits in some cases the observation of events as they actually occur in the spot being interrogated.  This combination of capabilities is unique and would provide the ability to study a host of systems in the areas of biology, chemistry, physics, and materials science.  
Our results have been disseminated in two peer reviewed publications.  One publication has been submitted.  Numerous presentations have been made at meetings and at other venues, such as universities.

The construction of the STED microscope and the research that it permits will enable a range of collaborative endeavors to be performed.    
Both students and postdocs have been trained on this device.  One of them, Sayantan Bose, is now a postdoc at Columbia University.



